This paper focuses on recognizing human activities in videos, which is a common task in computer vision. The paper proposes a new approach called Timeception, which uses multi-scale temporal convolutions to capture long-range temporal dependencies in complex actions. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). 

The paper also introduces a new type of convolution layer, which is designed to handle temporal information. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.MM (Multimedia), which deals with the processing and analysis of multimedia data. 

The paper also discusses the use of deep learning techniques, which suggests that it may be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

Finally, the paper focuses on recognizing human activities, which involves understanding natural language descriptions of actions. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language), which deals with natural language processing.
